{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:26:00.490527+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "## Triage Summary\n\n### Issue #1 – `apply_migrations.sh` applies files in wrong order on filesystems with case-folding\n\n**Status:** Confirmed bug  \n**Recommended labels:** `bug`, `priority/high`  \n**Action taken:** I was unable to add labels or a comment due to insufficient token permissions (403 errors on both operations). Below is the full triage analysis.\n\n---\n\n### Investigation\n\n1. **Migration files in `migrations/` (3 files, intended to run in order):**\n   - `001_create_users.sql` – Creates the `users` table.\n   - `002_create_sessions.sql` – Creates the `sessions` table (depends on `users`).\n   - `003_add_session_index.sql` – Creates an index on `sessions.user_id` (depends on `sessions`).\n\n2. **The script `scripts/apply_migrations.sh`** iterates with:\n   ```bash\n   for f in migrations/*.sql; do\n       echo \"Applying $f\"\n       docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\n   done\n   ```\n   The comment in the script acknowledges it \"relies on shell glob expansion ordering, not on `find`.\"\n\n3. **Why it fails on case-folding filesystems (e.g., macOS APFS):**\n   - Shell glob expansion sorting is **not guaranteed** to be consistent across filesystems, locales, or shell versions.\n   - On APFS (case-insensitive by default), `readdir` order is hash-based, and subsequent shell sorting depends on `LC_COLLATE`. On macOS, `LC_COLLATE` defaults to `en_US.UTF-8`, whose collation rules differ from the POSIX/C locale used on most Linux systems.\n   - The reporter observed `003_add_session_index.sql` being applied **first**, which causes `ERROR: relation \"sessions\" does not exist` because `002_create_sessions.sql` hasn't run yet.\n\n### Recommendation\n\nThe script should **explicitly sort** the files before iterating. Two possible fixes:\n\n**Option A – Portable (uses `find` + `sort`):**\n```bash\nfor f in $(find migrations -maxdepth 1 -name '*.sql' | sort); do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Option B – Bash-specific (keeps the glob but sorts explicitly):**\n```bash\nshopt -s nullglob\nfiles=(migrations/*.sql)\nIFS=$'\\n' sorted=($(sort <<<\"${files[*]}\")); unset IFS\nfor f in \"${sorted[@]}\"; do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n```\n\nEither ensures deterministic, lexicographic ordering regardless of filesystem or locale.\n\n---\n\n**Note:** I was unable to apply labels or post the above as a comment on the issue because the provided personal access token lacks the necessary permissions (403 Resource not accessible). The above analysis constitutes the triage output.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 811, "prompt_tokens": 13233, "total_tokens": 14044, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 110, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 13056}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 13056, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 177}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-flash", "system_fingerprint": "fp_8b330d02d0_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "af3adb9b-d1cf-42ea-baa3-d4a19821bc71", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3fa-567d-7122-9fc9-93c1fa110614-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13233, "output_tokens": 811, "total_tokens": 14044, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 13056}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 110}}}}]}}}
